				<p>
					We have learned a lot through the years about how to keep our children safe while riding in cars, but do parents know enough about how to keep kids safe from cars – an important consideration given that childhood pedestrian deaths are on the rise. The goal of the Pedestrian Safety Program at Children's National is to prevent such tragedies by providing pedestrian safety awareness and education to children and families of Washington, DC, and the surrounding metropolitan area.
				</p>
				<p>
					Recent statistics confirm that this type of intervention cannot come too soon: in 2011, 110,000 children under the age of 14 experienced injury as a pedestrian, and one in every five children between the ages of 5 and 9 killed in a traffic accident was a pedestrian. The Pedestrian Safety Program embraces a best practice model of community engagement as the most effective way to create sustainable change.  Last year, the program fostered relationships and provided education to school nurses, community leaders, and organizations, such as the Mayor’s Office on Latino Affairs, to assist in serving at-risk populations in the District of Columbia. Its work also included making information from Safe Kids and the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) easily accessible by including it on hospital websites and social media outlets. 
				</p>
				<p>
					The program has achieved impressive results since its inception! The 2011 campaign educated 1,300 families and five schools with significant Latino populations. In 2012, with 55 percent of reported injuries located in Ward 8, the campaign focused on that area, and with a push on International Walk to School Day, touched over 4,000 students. Furthering that outreach, the 2013 campaign involved visits to 26 elementary schools in Ward 8, providing every school nurse and nursing supervisor with educational and prevention tools that served over 9,500 families during the 2014 school year. Safety tips emailed to parents, community health fair screenings and education sessions, and stakeholder workshops were just a few of the additional outreach efforts last year aimed at involving the community at various levels in addressing this pressing problem. 
				</p>
