						<h3>Childhood Fall Prevention Program</h3>
						<img src="/assets/title_arrow_bg.png" />
					</div>
					<p>
						We lock our doors to keep our children safe, but what about our windows? Alarmingly, 5,100 children under age 18 are treated annually after falling from a second story or higher window. Even more disturbing: this rate has remained steady over the last 10 years, with over 98,000 children sustaining fall-related injuries. The Childhood Fall Prevention Program seeks to lower this number by joining with Safe Kids Maryland and other neighborhood partners to heighten awareness on the issue of accidental window falls. Program strategies are multi-faceted, and last year included educating local families on maintaining a window-safe home by using guardrails and window stops to prevent falls, as well as providing comprehensive training to 784 professionals, including healthcare providers, care givers, organizational leaders from programs such as Head Start, and prenatal/infant caregivers. A Public Service Announcement also was filmed to increase the outreach of this important program. With continued investment of resources in the community and in collaborative efforts, program staff expects to see a measurable decrease in the number of fall-related injuries in the very near future. 
